    <h1>ZAKKA IF YOU GOT THEM, FLAUNT THEM</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20210109/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2021-01-09"><time>2021-01-09</time></a>
        - <span>HOME DECOR</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>From the Ja­panese term kakka in de zakka, which trans­lates to</p>
    <p>“mis­cel­la­neous things”, Zakka is used to re­fer to Western house­hold items that were a nov­elty in Ja­pan dur­ing the ‘50s to ‘  0s but has since ex­panded to in­clude the mish­mash of things in one’s home. In con­trast to Min­i­mal­ism, this style en­cour­ages you to   ll your room with ob­jects but in an aes­thet­i­cally pleas­ing way.</p>
    <p>Got a mas­sive col­lec­tion of small items like toys, vinyls, or nov­elty spoons? Make them part of the home decor. House them prop­erly in­stead of let­ting them lan­guish in the store­room, or clut­ter the en­tire house.</p>
    <p>THE WORD ZAKKA IS DE­RIVED FROM THE JA­PANESE TERM KAKKAIN DEZAKKA, WHICH TRANS­LATES TO “MIS­CEL­LA­NEOUS THINGS”.</p>

